{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477724"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14708"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14708"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.14,0.78,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58116"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7401"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14708"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43575"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"2720"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18074"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58116"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent following two episodes of loss of consciousness in the past month. Before each episode, she experiences visual disturbances described as \u0027zigzag lines\u0027 and numbness in her right hand lasting about 15 minutes. She then develops a throbbing headache and nausea before briefly losing consciousness. She regains consciousness within one minute with no confusion. She has a history of occasional headaches but no other medical conditions and takes no regular medications. Her parent reports a family history of migraine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination is normal. Her heart sounds are normal with no murmurs. A 12-lead ECG shows normal sinus rhythm with normal intervals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vasovagal syncope","Complex partial seizures","Migraine-associated syncope","Cardiac arrhythmia","Psychogenic pseudosyncope"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a classic example of neurologic syncope in an adolescent. The key features supporting the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Emigraine-associated syncope\u003C/strong\u003E include the clear prodrome of focal neurologic symptoms (visual aura and parasthesias), followed by headache and brief loss of consciousness, with rapid recovery and no post-ictal state. The family history of migraine and normal cardiac examination further support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasovagal syncope\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of paediatric syncope, accounting for approximately 75% of cases. However, it typically occurs in response to specific triggers (such as prolonged standing, emotional stress, or pain) and is preceded by autonomic symptoms like lightheadedness, sweating, pallor, and nausea, rather than focal neurologic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplex partial seizures\u003C/strong\u003E can present with altered consciousness but typically last longer than one minute and are followed by a post-ictal period of confusion. The presence of a migraine-type headache and focal neurologic symptoms in a clear pattern makes seizures less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac arrhythmia\u003C/strong\u003E requires careful exclusion in any young person with syncope. However, the normal cardiac examination, normal ECG intervals, and presence of clear prodromal symptoms make this diagnosis unlikely. Cardiac syncope typically occurs without warning, often during exertion, and may be associated with chest pain or palpitations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychogenic pseudosyncope\u003C/strong\u003E can present with apparent loss of consciousness but typically has inconsistent features, prolonged duration, and often occurs multiple times per day. The stereotyped nature of the episodes with clear neurological symptoms makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of migraine-associated syncope includes migraine prophylaxis, lifestyle modifications, and patient education about recognising prodromal symptoms to prevent injury. A detailed history focusing on prodromal symptoms, triggers, and recovery pattern is essential in differentiating between causes of paediatric syncope.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Migraine-associated syncope is characterized by a prodrome of focal neurologic symptoms followed by headache and transient loss of consciousness.","A thorough history focusing on prodromal symptoms, triggers, and recovery is essential in differentiating causes of pediatric syncope.","Normal cardiac examination and ECG help exclude cardiac causes of syncope in children."],"references":["C\u00f4t\u00e9 JM. Syncope in children and adolescents: Evaluation and treatment. Paediatr Child Health. 2001 Oct;6(8):549-51. doi: 10.1093/pch/6.8.549. PMID: 20084125; PMCID: PMC2805591.","Anderson JB, Czosek RJ, Knilans TK, Marino BS. The evaluation and management of pediatric syncope. Pediatr Neurol. 2016;55:6-13."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43575"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14708"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43575"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-29T13:50:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T13:51:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7401"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58116"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","lin